you can find them at rstd.io slash rscloud-demo.

00:01:44.639 --> 00:01:47.040
I will show this link at the end as well.

00:01:47.040 --> 00:01:50.760
And there will be a bunch of kind of demos throughout.

00:01:50.760 --> 00:01:53.320
So the slides only give you a glimpse

00:01:53.320 --> 00:01:55.080
of part of what I'm going to say.

00:01:55.080 --> 00:01:57.080
But if you would like to get a hold of the PDF,

00:01:57.080 --> 00:01:58.440
you can do so there.

00:01:58.440 --> 00:02:00.160
So let's first talk a little bit

00:02:00.160 --> 00:02:02.680
about what RStudio Cloud is.

00:02:02.680 --> 00:02:04.480
RStudio Cloud looks just like this.

00:02:04.480 --> 00:02:08.440
When you land on rstudio.cloud and you log in,

00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:10.759
you can see that you have a place for your projects

00:02:10.759 --> 00:02:13.240
and you can start with a new project.

00:02:13.240 --> 00:02:15.839
And we'll start with an RStudio project for now.

00:02:15.839 --> 00:02:18.199
And you'll see that in my browser,

00:02:18.199 --> 00:02:20.800
I have something that looks just like RStudio

00:02:20.800 --> 00:02:23.880
if I had it locally on my computer as well.

00:02:23.880 --> 00:02:25.119
And I can give it a name.

00:02:25.119 --> 00:02:27.160
So that outer shell is a little bit different

00:02:27.160 --> 00:02:30.479
than what I tend to have locally on my computer

00:02:30.479 --> 00:02:32.600
where I can name my projects.

00:02:32.600 --> 00:02:34.520
But beyond that, I have my console.

00:02:34.520 --> 00:02:35.720
I have my environment tab.

00:02:35.720 --> 00:02:37.839
Everything is as I know it.

00:02:37.839 --> 00:02:40.160
What's happening is that the compute is happening

00:02:40.160 --> 00:02:43.520
on RStudio Cloud as opposed to happening on my computer.

00:02:43.520 --> 00:02:46.119
Well, what that tells me is that if this lives on the web,

00:02:46.119 --> 00:02:48.919
I should be able to easily share it with others as well.

00:02:48.919 --> 00:02:51.559
So a lot of what we're going to talk about today

00:02:51.559 --> 00:02:55.559
is not just how you create RStudio Cloud projects,

00:02:55.559 --> 00:02:57.960
but also how you share it with others,

00:02:57.960 --> 00:03:00.119
particularly in the context of teaching

00:03:00.119 --> 00:03:02.039
how you share it with your students.

00:03:02.960 --> 00:03:06.039
But before we get there, maybe let's answer the question,

00:03:06.039 --> 00:03:09.279
why would I want RStudio in the cloud in the first place?

00:03:09.279 --> 00:03:12.360
So instead of working locally, why might I want that?

00:03:12.360 --> 00:03:14.960
Well, particularly in the context of teaching,

00:03:14.960 --> 00:03:19.000
if you are going to be teaching R with RStudio,

00:03:19.919 --> 00:03:23.720
but your students are going to be using RStudio locally,

00:03:23.720 --> 00:03:25.080
they're going to have to do a few things

00:03:25.080 --> 00:03:26.520
when they get to the first class.

00:03:26.520 --> 00:03:27.919
They're going to have to install R.

00:03:27.919 --> 00:03:30.119
They're going to have to install RStudio.

00:03:30.119 --> 00:03:32.600
And they're going to have to install a bunch of packages

00:03:32.600 --> 00:03:35.080
that you might use throughout the semester.

00:03:36.279 --> 00:03:39.320
That's actually not that difficult necessarily,

00:03:39.320 --> 00:03:42.119
but you do have to utter these words to them, right?

00:03:42.880 --> 00:03:44.919
These things tend to work relatively easily

00:03:44.919 --> 00:03:47.000
for a majority of us,

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:49.360
but it becomes a thing you have to walk them through

00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:53.360
before you get to the exciting part of doing data analysis.

00:03:53.360 --> 00:03:55.160
Then you also need to talk to them a little bit

00:03:55.160 --> 00:03:58.399
about what's installing a package versus loading a package.

00:03:58.399 --> 00:04:00.600
And if you, like me, teach with version control,

00:04:00.600 --> 00:04:02.080
you also have to get your students

00:04:02.080 --> 00:04:05.320
to install Git locally on their computers as well.

00:04:05.320 --> 00:04:09.360
And trying to hit all five of these major bullet points

00:04:09.360 --> 00:04:11.160
in the first 10 minutes of the class

00:04:11.160 --> 00:04:12.880
is probably not going to happen.

00:04:12.880 --> 00:04:15.880
Realistically, you'll end up having to set aside

00:04:15.880 --> 00:04:18.799
a bunch of time for it and potentially do

00:04:18.799 --> 00:04:20.040
quite a bit of debugging

00:04:20.040 --> 00:04:22.279
for maybe a small number of your students,

00:04:22.279 --> 00:04:24.160
but there will be some who will get stuck

00:04:24.160 --> 00:04:25.519
on some of these stages.

00:04:26.559 --> 00:04:28.200
Instead of starting off your teaching

00:04:28.200 --> 00:04:29.720
with lots of friction points,

00:04:29.720 --> 00:04:31.920
you might want to be living in this land

00:04:31.920 --> 00:04:33.559
with much less friction,

00:04:33.559 --> 00:04:37.519
where you go to rstudio.cloud in your browser,

00:04:37.519 --> 00:04:40.160
you log in and you can start coding.

00:04:40.160 --> 00:04:43.160
What I'm always trying to get my students to,

00:04:43.160 --> 00:04:45.239
where I'm always trying to get my students

00:04:45.239 --> 00:04:47.600
is a place where when they sit down

00:04:47.600 --> 00:04:49.480
to work on their computer and they're like,

00:04:49.480 --> 00:04:51.119
all right, I'm going to work on my stats

00:04:51.119 --> 00:04:53.000
for my data science course,

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:55.720
it doesn't take them more work to get started

00:04:55.720 --> 00:04:58.880
than launching a video on Netflix, for example.

00:04:58.880 --> 00:05:01.160
And that's how easily you can get started

00:05:01.160 --> 00:05:03.799
with something like this.

00:05:03.799 --> 00:05:06.839
Now, we talked about why rstudio in the cloud.

00:05:06.839 --> 00:05:09.679
So where they go to could be rstudio.cloud

00:05:09.679 --> 00:05:11.880
or could be other options as well.

00:05:11.880 --> 00:05:16.440
So how do we achieve an access to rstudio in the cloud?

00:05:16.440 --> 00:05:19.040
One option is using the rstudio Workbench,

00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:21.679
which I'll just talk about briefly here

00:05:21.679 --> 00:05:23.040
and then move away from,

00:05:23.040 --> 00:05:27.519
but there may be reasons why this may be what you prefer.

00:05:27.519 --> 00:05:31.760
So if you have sysadmin experience yourself

00:05:31.760 --> 00:05:35.160
or IT support, perhaps from your university,

00:05:35.160 --> 00:05:37.359
and you also have some either hardware

00:05:37.359 --> 00:05:40.600
or a local virtual machine or some cloud computing credit

00:05:40.600 --> 00:05:42.839
where you could be running the compute.

00:05:42.839 --> 00:05:46.040
And obviously you yourself have a bit of rstudio experience

00:05:46.040 --> 00:05:47.519
to be teaching with it.

00:05:47.519 --> 00:05:49.679
This might be an option for you.

00:05:49.679 --> 00:05:52.559
So rstudio offers rstudio Workbench,

00:05:52.559 --> 00:05:56.519
which you can run in your browser

00:05:56.519 --> 00:05:59.079
once it's been set up for you.

00:05:59.079 --> 00:06:03.000
And you can get the software for teaching purposes

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:04.600
for free from rstudio.

00:06:04.600 --> 00:06:05.839
And I've put on the slide,

00:06:05.839 --> 00:06:08.119
the link to our academic pricing page,

00:06:08.119 --> 00:06:09.959
if you'd like to take a look to find out more

00:06:09.959 --> 00:06:11.079
about that offering.

00:06:12.760 --> 00:06:15.079
If you would like to set things up in this way,

00:06:15.079 --> 00:06:16.279
there is a bit of setup.

00:06:16.279 --> 00:06:18.200
And that's why I have the first bullet point

00:06:18.200 --> 00:06:20.640
about either having sysadmin experience

00:06:20.640 --> 00:06:22.920
or IT support available to you.

00:06:22.920 --> 00:06:25.519
But if those are things that you are able to do,

00:06:25.519 --> 00:06:27.440
and you are able to set things up in a way

00:06:27.440 --> 00:06:30.000
that where your students can authenticate

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:31.839
and use the platform,

00:06:32.839 --> 00:06:37.839
do, you may find this article we have

00:06:38.119 --> 00:06:40.359
in the American Statistician called

00:06:40.359 --> 00:06:43.119
Infrastructure and Tools for Teaching Computing

00:06:43.119 --> 00:06:45.320
throughout the statistical curriculum helpful,

00:06:45.320 --> 00:06:48.839
where we describe our setup that we have at Duke University,

00:06:48.839 --> 00:06:51.359
where we use a version of the setup

00:06:51.359 --> 00:06:55.480
for getting our students to do computing in their browser.

00:06:57.040 --> 00:07:00.600
Another option is instead of having to,

00:07:00.720 --> 00:07:02.839
needing to have all three of these,

00:07:02.839 --> 00:07:05.600
if you just have RStudio experience yourself

00:07:05.600 --> 00:07:06.799
as an instructor,

00:07:06.799 --> 00:07:09.079
but maybe not the sysadmin experience

00:07:09.079 --> 00:07:11.040
and not the kind of the machine

00:07:11.040 --> 00:07:12.920
where you could be running this on,

00:07:12.920 --> 00:07:16.119
RStudio Cloud might be the right option for you.

00:07:16.119 --> 00:07:19.559
So the setup is a lot less cumbersome

00:07:19.559 --> 00:07:22.640
and a lot less resource intensive.

00:07:22.640 --> 00:07:26.160
So that's what we're going to be mostly talking about today.

00:07:26.160 --> 00:07:28.359
Now that hopefully we've set the stage

00:07:28.359 --> 00:07:31.799
for there may be a pedagogical need

00:07:31.799 --> 00:07:34.760
for getting your students to start computing in the cloud

00:07:34.760 --> 00:07:36.160
as opposed to locally,

00:07:36.160 --> 00:07:39.000
and kind of giving you a lay of the land

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:42.399
of what are your options for doing this with RStudio.

00:07:43.239 --> 00:07:46.679
Let's talk a little bit more about why RStudio Cloud.

00:07:46.679 --> 00:07:48.959
Beyond the fact that it does not require

00:07:48.959 --> 00:07:51.000
IT experience to set up,

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:53.880
it also has some really nice bells and whistles

00:07:53.880 --> 00:07:56.359
that are designed particularly for teaching.

00:07:56.399 --> 00:07:59.760
For example, there is the notion of a workspace

00:07:59.760 --> 00:08:02.320
where you can organize your class as a workspace.

00:08:02.320 --> 00:08:04.480
So either if you're teaching multiple classes

00:08:04.480 --> 00:08:05.799
in the same semester,

00:08:05.799 --> 00:08:07.320
or from semester to semester,

00:08:07.320 --> 00:08:10.920
you're able to kind of have them organized

00:08:10.920 --> 00:08:13.320
in a nicely contained way.

00:08:13.320 --> 00:08:14.959
There is a notion of roles.

00:08:14.959 --> 00:08:18.279
So things like instructor, teaching assistant or student

00:08:18.279 --> 00:08:22.279
can be assigned to particular roles on RStudio Cloud.

00:08:22.279 --> 00:08:23.799
You can turn your project.

00:08:23.799 --> 00:08:25.359
So I just showed you earlier

00:08:25.359 --> 00:08:28.079
how to fire up a project in RStudio Cloud.

00:08:28.079 --> 00:08:29.839
You can turn that into an assignment

00:08:29.839 --> 00:08:33.320
that your students can quickly get started with.

00:08:33.320 --> 00:08:36.479
And as an instructor, something I really, really like

00:08:36.479 --> 00:08:39.679
is that you can peek into student projects.

00:08:39.679 --> 00:08:43.200
So that is really very similar to being able to,

00:08:43.200 --> 00:08:47.400
you know, be say in a computer lab with your students.

00:08:47.400 --> 00:08:49.640
And if they have a question

00:08:49.640 --> 00:08:51.520
kind of peeking over their shoulder,

00:08:51.520 --> 00:08:55.080
and being able to do this has been particularly helpful

00:08:55.760 --> 00:08:58.880
when we've had to do a bunch of remote teaching.

00:08:58.880 --> 00:09:01.919
The other thing is that you can set up a base project

00:09:01.919 --> 00:09:05.440
that contains any R packages you might need,

00:09:05.440 --> 00:09:07.080
or any other documentation

00:09:07.080 --> 00:09:09.479
that you would like for your students to have

00:09:11.559 --> 00:09:13.359
for every single one of their projects.

00:09:13.359 --> 00:09:14.760
You can set that up for them

00:09:14.760 --> 00:09:17.119
and modify it throughout the semester,

00:09:17.119 --> 00:09:19.960
and ensure that each time a student starts a new project,

00:09:19.960 --> 00:09:22.679
they're all starting with the same base project.

00:09:23.679 --> 00:09:26.320
Certain system libraries work out of the box.

00:09:26.320 --> 00:09:30.400
For example, Git will work out of the box.

00:09:30.400 --> 00:09:33.239
And also you can render to PDF or Word,

00:09:33.239 --> 00:09:35.559
and that works out of the box as well.

00:09:35.559 --> 00:09:38.960
These are generally things for local use.

00:09:38.960 --> 00:09:41.320
The user would have to set up themselves,

00:09:41.320 --> 00:09:44.679
or if you are teaching in a situation

00:09:44.679 --> 00:09:49.239
where your students are using their local setup,

00:09:49.239 --> 00:09:51.440
they would have to install for themselves.

00:09:51.599 --> 00:09:54.080
And usually the installation and setup of these

00:09:54.080 --> 00:09:56.039
tends to require more skills

00:09:56.039 --> 00:09:59.280
than just being able to do some computing with R.

00:10:00.719 --> 00:10:04.359
All right, so now that we've kind of done an introduction

00:10:04.359 --> 00:10:06.799
to RStudio Cloud, I'd like to do a few demos

00:10:06.799 --> 00:10:09.520
where I can actually take you through RStudio Cloud

00:10:09.520 --> 00:10:10.799
and talk a little bit,

00:10:10.799 --> 00:10:12.200
and show you a little bit about

00:10:12.200 --> 00:10:14.400
how life in RStudio Cloud works.

00:10:14.400 --> 00:10:16.919
So let's start with this notion of a project.

00:10:16.919 --> 00:10:21.159
So this is what an RStudio Cloud project

00:10:21.159 --> 00:10:22.200
looks like.

00:10:22.200 --> 00:10:25.359
And here I am in an RStudio session.

00:10:25.359 --> 00:10:30.359
And if you do use RStudio locally as well,

00:10:30.559 --> 00:10:34.159
this is basically the same idea as a local project.

00:10:35.080 --> 00:10:37.159
And there is a nice UI, as I said,

00:10:37.159 --> 00:10:39.080
up top as a banner,

00:10:39.080 --> 00:10:40.479
where you can kind of keep track of

00:10:40.479 --> 00:10:42.239
which project you're working on.

00:10:43.719 --> 00:10:45.440
Another thing that you can do

00:10:45.440 --> 00:10:47.559
is so when we're starting up a new project,

00:10:47.559 --> 00:10:50.559
you can actually open up a Jupyter project as well.

00:10:50.559 --> 00:10:54.440
So this is currently in beta, but it is available.

00:10:54.440 --> 00:10:55.919
And when you fire this up,

00:10:55.919 --> 00:10:59.039
you basically get an IPython notebook.

00:10:59.039 --> 00:11:01.960
And you can see that in the same environment.

00:11:01.960 --> 00:11:04.719
So I've just, I'm still in RStudio Cloud,

00:11:04.719 --> 00:11:08.159
but I'm able to run a Jupyter notebook as well.

00:11:09.119 --> 00:11:11.960
And you can see just like a regular Jupyter notebook,

00:11:11.960 --> 00:11:14.479
I have a little bit of kind of text

00:11:14.479 --> 00:11:16.919
and a little bit of code intermingled

00:11:16.919 --> 00:11:20.000
and I can run my cells, so on and so forth.

00:11:21.559 --> 00:11:24.479
Other things that you can do

00:11:24.479 --> 00:11:28.119
is you can also start with a project from a Git repository.

00:11:28.119 --> 00:11:31.080
So you can simply put the kind of the URL

00:11:31.080 --> 00:11:32.640
of your Git repository here.

00:11:32.640 --> 00:11:35.159
I'm cloning the praise package.

00:11:35.159 --> 00:11:37.559
That is an R package that, you know,

00:11:37.559 --> 00:11:40.479
gives you nice pleasantries as you run your code,

00:11:40.479 --> 00:11:43.440
gives you some positive reinforcement.

00:11:43.440 --> 00:11:46.400
And you can see that I'm able to clone that project

00:11:46.400 --> 00:11:49.159
and kind of start working with that as well.

00:11:49.200 --> 00:11:53.640
This does require that you kind of sync up

00:11:53.640 --> 00:11:56.679
your GitHub account with your RStudio Cloud account,

00:11:56.679 --> 00:11:59.080
which you can do so from your profile.

00:11:59.080 --> 00:12:00.640
But once that's all set up,

00:12:00.640 --> 00:12:03.359
you're able to interact with Git easily as well.

00:12:06.359 --> 00:12:09.200
So teaching with RStudio Cloud

00:12:09.200 --> 00:12:11.119
beyond just using it for yourself

00:12:11.119 --> 00:12:15.880
really does not require any further kind of setup than this,

00:12:15.880 --> 00:12:18.119
except the fact that you probably will want

00:12:18.119 --> 00:12:21.799
to prepare some projects for your students,

00:12:21.799 --> 00:12:23.919
and you might be thinking about various ways

00:12:23.919 --> 00:12:25.719
that you can share it with them.

00:12:25.719 --> 00:12:29.080
So there are really two ways that I think about teaching

00:12:29.080 --> 00:12:31.159
when I'm kind of thinking about

00:12:31.159 --> 00:12:33.520
what sort of sharing approach

00:12:33.520 --> 00:12:35.479
I'm going to use for my students.

00:12:35.479 --> 00:12:38.280
Often I ask myself the question,

00:12:38.280 --> 00:12:39.960
is this a shorter engagement,

00:12:39.960 --> 00:12:42.679
something like a workshop or a short course,

00:12:42.679 --> 00:12:47.359
where I can organize content in a single RStudio project

00:12:47.359 --> 00:12:49.400
or just a few projects,

00:12:49.400 --> 00:12:53.039
and I have no need for keeping track of my learners.

00:12:53.039 --> 00:12:54.960
So that's usually for me a setting

00:12:54.960 --> 00:12:57.200
where maybe I won't be grading them,

00:12:57.200 --> 00:12:59.520
or I'm not necessarily responsible

00:12:59.520 --> 00:13:01.359
for keeping track of their work

00:13:01.359 --> 00:13:04.119
over an extended period of time.

00:13:04.119 --> 00:13:05.239
If that's the case,

00:13:05.239 --> 00:13:08.239
you can simply create a project like we've shown before

00:13:08.239 --> 00:13:11.919
and share that project simply by sharing its URL.

00:13:11.919 --> 00:13:14.280
If you have a longer engagement,

00:13:14.280 --> 00:13:17.039
so that is perhaps a semester long course

00:13:17.719 --> 00:13:20.520
or a multi-day workshop where there's lots of content.

00:13:20.520 --> 00:13:22.679
And instead of kind of putting all of that

00:13:22.679 --> 00:13:26.359
into a single or just a few RStudio projects,

00:13:26.359 --> 00:13:29.000
you can think about it as many, many projects

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:31.239
that need to happen throughout a semester.

00:13:31.239 --> 00:13:33.400
So maybe many homework assignments,

00:13:33.400 --> 00:13:37.080
a final project, some lab work, so on and so forth.

00:13:37.080 --> 00:13:39.599
And you have a need or desire

00:13:39.599 --> 00:13:41.719
to keep track of your learners,

00:13:41.719 --> 00:13:43.440
either for grading purposes,

00:13:43.440 --> 00:13:45.320
or because you want to assess

00:13:45.320 --> 00:13:48.000
either for your kind of enjoyment

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:51.039
or to be able to give feedback to the students,

00:13:51.039 --> 00:13:55.080
how much they're interacting with both the platform

00:13:55.080 --> 00:13:56.640
and also the learning materials

00:13:56.640 --> 00:13:58.400
that you've prepared for them.

00:13:58.400 --> 00:14:01.320
In that case, I recommend creating a workspace

00:14:01.320 --> 00:14:04.520
and then inviting your students to that workspace.

00:14:04.520 --> 00:14:07.320
So I'm going to demo both of these approaches next.

00:14:07.320 --> 00:14:11.479
So let's start with sharing an RStudio Cloud project.

00:14:11.479 --> 00:14:13.719
So we're in the instructor view here.

00:14:13.760 --> 00:14:18.400
You can see that I have prepared a single RStudio project.

00:14:18.400 --> 00:14:20.119
And I have a few folders in there

00:14:20.119 --> 00:14:22.520
where I've organized my teaching materials.

00:14:22.520 --> 00:14:24.039
This happens to be a short course

00:14:24.039 --> 00:14:26.039
I gave on introduction to Shiny.

00:14:26.039 --> 00:14:28.719
So we have four modules in this short course,

00:14:28.719 --> 00:14:32.760
and I've created those and put them in my files pane.

00:14:32.760 --> 00:14:36.080
And what I'm going to do is

00:14:36.080 --> 00:14:39.400
I can kind of show you the inside these folders.

00:14:39.400 --> 00:14:42.679
We can see that I have kind of the R scripts

00:14:42.679 --> 00:14:45.239
that I want to share with my learners.

00:14:45.239 --> 00:14:49.000
And I also have packages installed as well.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:52.640
So I am installing any packages

00:14:52.640 --> 00:14:57.640
that I'm going to use in this short course for my students

00:14:58.200 --> 00:15:01.200
so that when they come in, they can simply run the code

00:15:01.200 --> 00:15:02.799
and they don't have to worry

00:15:02.799 --> 00:15:05.080
about installing packages as well.

00:15:05.080 --> 00:15:07.280
It's not that difficult to install packages,

00:15:07.280 --> 00:15:09.679
but this ensures that everybody is using

00:15:09.679 --> 00:15:11.719
the same version of the package.

00:15:13.080 --> 00:15:15.359
I have prepared everything for them.

00:15:15.359 --> 00:15:20.239
And what I can do next is make my project shareable.

00:15:20.239 --> 00:15:23.119
It's private by default, but I can go to access

00:15:23.119 --> 00:15:26.919
and say, anyone can view this project now

00:15:26.919 --> 00:15:28.960
and just grab its URL.

00:15:28.960 --> 00:15:31.159
Now, when I say anyone can view the project,

00:15:31.159 --> 00:15:35.960
I should mention that even though anyone can now see this,

00:15:35.960 --> 00:15:37.799
it's only if I share the URL with them.

00:15:37.799 --> 00:15:39.960
It's kind of privacy by obscurity.

00:15:39.960 --> 00:15:42.559
You can see that URL has some random numbers

00:15:43.440 --> 00:15:45.840
at the end and just about anyone couldn't just guess

00:15:45.840 --> 00:15:47.080
what that is, obviously.

00:15:47.080 --> 00:15:52.080
So I'm going to have to kind of grab that URL

00:15:52.239 --> 00:15:54.400
now that I've enabled sharing.

00:15:54.400 --> 00:15:57.960
And then I share that with my learners.

00:15:57.960 --> 00:15:59.440
So I maybe email it to them

00:15:59.440 --> 00:16:01.440
or message it to them or something.

00:16:01.440 --> 00:16:04.840
And all they need to do is put that in their browser

00:16:04.840 --> 00:16:07.400
and they're gonna need to log in.

00:16:07.400 --> 00:16:10.039
They might choose to log in with Google or GitHub

00:16:10.039 --> 00:16:14.840
or something else or like an RStudio cloud account.

00:16:14.840 --> 00:16:17.880
And you can see that they're in the same

00:16:17.880 --> 00:16:19.320
kind of looking environment

00:16:19.320 --> 00:16:22.159
and they don't need to install a package anymore.

00:16:22.159 --> 00:16:23.880
They can simply load a package

00:16:23.880 --> 00:16:26.880
because the package for them is already installed

00:16:26.880 --> 00:16:31.159
and they have the same file structure as I have

00:16:31.159 --> 00:16:33.840
and they're able to run the code.

00:16:33.840 --> 00:16:37.039
I want to grab your attention or point your attention

00:16:37.039 --> 00:16:38.239
to one more thing here,

00:16:38.239 --> 00:16:40.479
just under student view on my slide,

00:16:40.479 --> 00:16:42.440
it says temporary copy.

00:16:42.440 --> 00:16:44.880
So when a student receives this link,

00:16:44.880 --> 00:16:48.280
they're in a temporary copy of this project.

00:16:48.280 --> 00:16:50.840
And what they can do is next to that,

00:16:50.840 --> 00:16:53.200
there's a button that says save a permanent copy

00:16:53.200 --> 00:16:54.840
and they can make it their own.

00:16:54.840 --> 00:16:57.599
At that point, RStudio cloud is simply grabbing

00:16:57.599 --> 00:16:59.640
a snapshot of that project

00:16:59.640 --> 00:17:01.840
and making a copy for the student

00:17:01.840 --> 00:17:03.880
that they can continue working on.

00:17:03.880 --> 00:17:05.680
And when they come back,

00:17:05.680 --> 00:17:08.640
they're able to continue working on their own copy

00:17:08.640 --> 00:17:10.800
and any changes they make basically

00:17:10.800 --> 00:17:14.160
does not propagate back to my project

00:17:14.160 --> 00:17:16.400
and also does not get lost either.

00:17:18.319 --> 00:17:21.719
So this idea of sharing an RStudio cloud project

00:17:21.719 --> 00:17:24.760
on the plus side is super easy.

00:17:24.760 --> 00:17:26.599
First of all, I created my project

00:17:26.599 --> 00:17:29.880
and all I had to do was to flip a switch for shareability

00:17:29.880 --> 00:17:31.719
and share the URL.

00:17:31.719 --> 00:17:33.520
Other pluses associated with it

00:17:33.520 --> 00:17:37.000
is that students land directly in a project upon login.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:39.680
So, you know, we're telling them we're teaching RStudio

00:17:39.680 --> 00:17:42.079
and we give them a URL and they're right there.

00:17:42.079 --> 00:17:44.839
There's no additional steps they need to do.

00:17:44.839 --> 00:17:47.479
I find that beyond teaching,

00:17:47.479 --> 00:17:49.880
this sort of sharing a project

00:17:49.880 --> 00:17:53.319
is actually great for just collaboration,

00:17:53.319 --> 00:17:55.359
particularly if I have collaborators

00:17:55.359 --> 00:17:57.839
with whom I want to share my code,

00:17:57.839 --> 00:18:00.560
but maybe they're not, you know, Git or GitHub users.

00:18:00.560 --> 00:18:02.800
So that's not the path we want to go

00:18:02.839 --> 00:18:05.439
or to create some reproducible examples

00:18:05.439 --> 00:18:09.400
that might be a bit more, you know,

00:18:09.400 --> 00:18:13.560
a bit more extensive than like a little snippet

00:18:13.560 --> 00:18:17.079
you might share with somebody on Slack or GitHub.

00:18:17.079 --> 00:18:19.680
So oftentimes if I'm trying to debug,

00:18:19.680 --> 00:18:22.000
for example, an extensive Shiny app,

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:24.160
even if I make it pretty minimal,

00:18:24.160 --> 00:18:26.119
I find that there's a lot of code there

00:18:26.119 --> 00:18:28.199
to just post into a message.

00:18:28.199 --> 00:18:31.920
So often I'll create a single RStudio cloud project

00:18:31.959 --> 00:18:34.160
and then it ends up having the packages

00:18:34.160 --> 00:18:36.439
that I have installed ready to go as well

00:18:36.439 --> 00:18:39.280
to share with somebody else to ask a question.

00:18:39.280 --> 00:18:41.520
Now on the negative side,

00:18:41.520 --> 00:18:45.479
that temporary copy thing with even with the handy

00:18:45.479 --> 00:18:48.079
save a permanent copy button next to it

00:18:48.079 --> 00:18:51.599
can sometimes get students because they need to remember

00:18:51.599 --> 00:18:54.680
to make a permanent copy of the project,

00:18:54.680 --> 00:18:57.199
which honestly, as an instructor to you

00:18:57.199 --> 00:19:00.400
means you need to remind them to do so.

00:19:00.400 --> 00:19:02.439
Otherwise their work can get lost.

00:19:03.680 --> 00:19:04.959
Also as an instructor,

00:19:04.959 --> 00:19:07.280
you can't keep track of which students

00:19:07.280 --> 00:19:08.560
started their assignments

00:19:08.560 --> 00:19:10.839
because once they make a copy, they own that.

00:19:10.839 --> 00:19:15.839
And if they want you to take a look at their project,

00:19:16.160 --> 00:19:18.160
you need to be granted permission back.

00:19:18.160 --> 00:19:19.760
You don't have that by default,

00:19:19.760 --> 00:19:22.359
even though you have originally shared it with them.

00:19:23.400 --> 00:19:27.000
The permanent other things that could be a plus or a minus,

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:30.280
depending on your situation is that these permanent projects

00:19:31.160 --> 00:19:32.959
once the student makes the permanent project,

00:19:32.959 --> 00:19:35.400
they count towards their student's free account.

00:19:35.400 --> 00:19:38.439
So if you're an instructor who is not wanting

00:19:38.439 --> 00:19:42.160
to kind of use up your account's usage,

00:19:42.160 --> 00:19:43.920
that might be a plus.

00:19:43.920 --> 00:19:45.880
But if you're an instructor who is thinking,

00:19:45.880 --> 00:19:48.040
I would like to make sure that I'm offering this

00:19:48.040 --> 00:19:51.280
to my students for free forever,

00:19:51.280 --> 00:19:53.920
this may not be the right setup for you.

00:19:53.920 --> 00:19:56.880
Also students control permissions on their project.

00:19:56.880 --> 00:19:59.800
This can also be a pro or a con.

00:20:00.319 --> 00:20:02.400
It's nice for them to have this control,

00:20:02.400 --> 00:20:05.079
but that might also mean that they are sharing it

00:20:05.079 --> 00:20:06.040
very liberally.

00:20:06.040 --> 00:20:09.880
So if you're teaching in a setting where,

00:20:10.920 --> 00:20:14.079
things like maybe giving an assignment

00:20:14.079 --> 00:20:17.160
that students should not be collaborating on in any way,

00:20:17.160 --> 00:20:19.040
should not see each other's code,

00:20:19.920 --> 00:20:22.920
this might make it easier for them to do something

00:20:22.920 --> 00:20:24.359
that they're not supposed to do.

00:20:24.359 --> 00:20:28.000
Obviously, disallowing this sort of

00:20:28.040 --> 00:20:31.400
permissions from the students,

00:20:31.400 --> 00:20:33.760
does not mean you're going to be insured

00:20:33.760 --> 00:20:36.520
that no academic dishonesty occurs.

00:20:36.520 --> 00:20:39.119
But generally my motto when I'm teaching is,

00:20:39.119 --> 00:20:43.199
I try to not make it additionally easier for my students

00:20:43.199 --> 00:20:45.599
to do something that I don't want them to do.

00:20:45.599 --> 00:20:48.479
So if you're giving assignments and you're saying,

00:20:48.479 --> 00:20:50.880
you can't see each other's code,

00:20:50.880 --> 00:20:53.800
this may again, may not be the right approach for you.

00:20:54.800 --> 00:20:57.400
So we've talked about creating a single project

00:20:57.400 --> 00:20:58.400
and sharing that.

00:20:58.400 --> 00:21:01.199
And I mentioned that this is a useful approach

00:21:01.199 --> 00:21:03.319
for kind of short engagements,

00:21:03.319 --> 00:21:05.680
but what about for longer engagements

00:21:05.680 --> 00:21:08.920
where maybe you're teaching a semester long course

00:21:08.920 --> 00:21:11.079
and you need things a little better organized.

00:21:11.079 --> 00:21:13.800
So in that case, the approach that you might take

00:21:13.800 --> 00:21:18.119
is inviting your students to an RStudio Cloud workspace.

00:21:18.119 --> 00:21:21.000
So I'm again here on the instructor view,

00:21:21.640 --> 00:21:24.880
and you can say that on the top bar,

00:21:24.880 --> 00:21:27.439
it says your workspace.

00:21:27.439 --> 00:21:29.760
So what I'm going to do is I'm going to click

00:21:29.760 --> 00:21:34.079
on the little menu next to it and create a new space.

00:21:34.079 --> 00:21:36.199
So in this case, I'm creating a space

00:21:36.199 --> 00:21:39.040
for a new course that I'm giving,

00:21:39.040 --> 00:21:41.239
I'll call that Shiny Essentials.

00:21:41.239 --> 00:21:45.040
And now that I have moved into this new workspace,

00:21:45.040 --> 00:21:47.800
I can create projects in here.

00:21:47.800 --> 00:21:50.640
So these projects are only going to be accessible

00:21:51.280 --> 00:21:52.599
to folks that are in this workspace.

00:21:52.599 --> 00:21:56.640
So I can similarly create modules

00:21:56.640 --> 00:22:00.319
for my students to learn from,

00:22:00.319 --> 00:22:05.239
and I can set things up in many ways.

00:22:05.239 --> 00:22:08.040
So when I go to share this project,

00:22:08.040 --> 00:22:12.800
you can see that it now says everyone in Shiny Essentials,

00:22:12.800 --> 00:22:16.599
and it allows me to turn it into an assignment as well.

00:22:16.839 --> 00:22:20.959
What this means is when the students land in this workspace,

00:22:20.959 --> 00:22:23.160
they're going to see this first project,

00:22:23.160 --> 00:22:25.599
and it says instead of assignment next to it,

00:22:25.599 --> 00:22:27.319
it will say start for them.

00:22:27.319 --> 00:22:30.959
So they can get started with a permanent copy of their own

00:22:30.959 --> 00:22:33.839
that lives in this RStudio Cloud workspace.

00:22:33.839 --> 00:22:35.400
So they don't have to remember

00:22:35.400 --> 00:22:37.920
to make a copy for themselves.

00:22:39.640 --> 00:22:43.400
Once students have started their assignments,

00:22:43.439 --> 00:22:47.239
I as the instructor can track their projects as well.

00:22:47.239 --> 00:22:48.479
So in this case,

00:22:48.479 --> 00:22:51.479
I was teaching this Shiny Essentials course,

00:22:51.479 --> 00:22:53.640
and over the four modules,

00:22:53.640 --> 00:22:58.520
you can see that there are many kind of derived projects

00:22:58.520 --> 00:22:59.560
from each of these.

00:22:59.560 --> 00:23:04.520
So 187 students came to this project

00:23:04.520 --> 00:23:07.079
and they made their own permanent copies

00:23:07.079 --> 00:23:08.959
and they started working on them.

00:23:08.959 --> 00:23:10.560
And I can actually go in,

00:23:10.599 --> 00:23:14.199
I can click on that view derived projects link,

00:23:14.199 --> 00:23:16.839
and I can go in and see my students' names

00:23:16.839 --> 00:23:19.560
and even open up their RStudio Cloud projects.

00:23:19.560 --> 00:23:22.520
So if somebody is having difficulty

00:23:22.520 --> 00:23:25.079
to the point where we're unable to like help them

00:23:25.079 --> 00:23:29.479
get unstuck by maybe discussion forum posts or something,

00:23:29.479 --> 00:23:31.959
I can actually go in and directly help them

00:23:31.959 --> 00:23:33.680
in their RStudio session.

00:23:34.680 --> 00:23:36.479
Another thing is,

00:23:36.479 --> 00:23:40.400
so how do we get students into this workspace?

00:23:40.400 --> 00:23:44.439
Under the members tab within your workspace,

00:23:44.439 --> 00:23:46.640
you can see the names of your members.

00:23:46.640 --> 00:23:49.680
So I have grayed those out for privacy reasons,

00:23:49.680 --> 00:23:52.079
but you can see that I can scroll through

00:23:52.079 --> 00:23:55.640
and see who the members are of this workspace.

00:23:55.640 --> 00:24:00.199
And I can invite more folks either via an invitation.

00:24:00.199 --> 00:24:02.280
So I would need to enter their email address

00:24:02.280 --> 00:24:05.479
and send it to them, or I can use a sharing link.

00:24:05.479 --> 00:24:07.560
So I can create a sharing link,

00:24:07.560 --> 00:24:11.359
set a particular default role for that sharing link

00:24:11.359 --> 00:24:14.359
and simply share the link with them.

00:24:14.359 --> 00:24:16.839
And at some point I can reset that link if I want,

00:24:16.839 --> 00:24:21.760
if I want no further people to continue to join the workspace.

00:24:21.760 --> 00:24:24.239
So these particular roles are admin,

00:24:24.239 --> 00:24:27.439
moderator, contributor, and viewer.

00:24:27.439 --> 00:24:30.959
I think about these as the admin is the instructor.

00:24:30.959 --> 00:24:32.319
Admin is the instructor.

00:24:32.319 --> 00:24:33.160
So that's me.

00:24:33.160 --> 00:24:34.319
I can do whatever I want.

00:24:34.319 --> 00:24:35.400
I can manage users.

00:24:35.400 --> 00:24:38.959
I can view, edit, and manage all of the projects.

00:24:38.959 --> 00:24:42.640
The moderator level to me in an instructional setting

00:24:42.640 --> 00:24:44.000
is more like my TA.

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:46.359
They can view, edit, and manage all projects,

00:24:46.359 --> 00:24:50.119
but they don't have the privileges to get more people in

00:24:50.119 --> 00:24:52.640
or kick people out of the class.

00:24:52.640 --> 00:24:54.599
A contributor are my students.

00:24:54.599 --> 00:24:58.800
They can create, edit, and manage their own projects only.

00:24:58.800 --> 00:25:01.439
They don't get to touch other people's projects.

00:25:01.439 --> 00:25:04.680
And then the viewer role is something that I think that,

00:25:04.680 --> 00:25:07.520
you know, that you may not even use at all,

00:25:07.520 --> 00:25:09.520
but instances where I've used it

00:25:09.520 --> 00:25:13.760
have been either auditors to the class or guests.

00:25:13.760 --> 00:25:16.319
So these people can only view projects

00:25:16.319 --> 00:25:19.520
that are shared with everyone and no other projects.

00:25:20.719 --> 00:25:23.640
Sometimes I have colleagues who want to,

00:25:25.079 --> 00:25:27.319
who want to perhaps take a peek

00:25:27.319 --> 00:25:29.880
at what's happening in my class

00:25:29.880 --> 00:25:31.479
to kind of take a look to see

00:25:31.479 --> 00:25:36.479
how I've set up my RStudio Cloud workspace, for example,

00:25:36.800 --> 00:25:39.719
but I perhaps don't want them to see my students' names

00:25:39.719 --> 00:25:41.400
or their projects.

00:25:41.400 --> 00:25:44.640
So that's the role I have mostly used that for.

00:25:46.680 --> 00:25:48.359
We can also set permissions

00:25:48.359 --> 00:25:51.319
and these come unchecked by default.

00:25:51.319 --> 00:25:53.479
And I would recommend leaving them that way

00:25:53.479 --> 00:25:55.880
unless you have good reason to do so.

00:25:56.040 --> 00:25:57.239
One of them, for example,

00:25:57.239 --> 00:26:00.560
is about whether contributors can see the members list.

00:26:00.560 --> 00:26:02.239
Another one is whether they can,

00:26:02.239 --> 00:26:05.199
contributors can make their projects visible to all members.

00:26:05.199 --> 00:26:07.199
I usually leave that unchecked

00:26:07.199 --> 00:26:08.599
because I don't want my students

00:26:08.599 --> 00:26:11.719
to readily share their assignments with each other.

00:26:11.719 --> 00:26:14.119
And then there's other settings

00:26:14.119 --> 00:26:16.040
in terms of what the viewers can do

00:26:16.040 --> 00:26:19.319
and who can change the computational resources.

00:26:19.319 --> 00:26:21.079
And I'll talk a little bit about what I mean

00:26:21.079 --> 00:26:23.560
by computational resources in a little bit.

00:26:24.560 --> 00:26:29.560
Another perk of using this workspace setting

00:26:30.199 --> 00:26:32.359
is perhaps my favorite one

00:26:32.359 --> 00:26:35.959
is this notion of a base RStudio project.

00:26:35.959 --> 00:26:39.839
So what that is is a project that you can set.

00:26:39.839 --> 00:26:43.280
So it's an RStudio project that you can set to say,

00:26:43.280 --> 00:26:47.040
this is the image I want every single project to start with.

00:26:48.160 --> 00:26:52.599
So I can actually put, decide on the version of R

00:26:52.599 --> 00:26:54.280
I want everyone to use,

00:26:54.280 --> 00:26:56.800
the installed packages and their versions

00:26:56.800 --> 00:26:58.640
that I want everyone to use,

00:26:58.640 --> 00:27:02.319
and also any files that I want every single project

00:27:02.319 --> 00:27:04.319
in my workspace to contain.

00:27:04.319 --> 00:27:06.439
Usually for me, those are things like

00:27:06.439 --> 00:27:08.959
a statement of code of conduct,

00:27:08.959 --> 00:27:12.400
maybe some instructions for how to submit work.

00:27:12.400 --> 00:27:13.680
They're not things that change

00:27:13.680 --> 00:27:15.079
from assignment to assignment.

00:27:15.079 --> 00:27:17.520
They're things that need to stay constant.

00:27:17.520 --> 00:27:20.119
They're the sort of things you might tell your students,

00:27:20.119 --> 00:27:21.959
go read in the syllabus.

00:27:21.959 --> 00:27:23.959
So I ended up putting those there.

00:27:25.280 --> 00:27:29.280
These base projects can be updated throughout the semester,

00:27:29.280 --> 00:27:31.599
which means that say a newer version

00:27:31.599 --> 00:27:33.160
of a package you use comes

00:27:33.160 --> 00:27:34.760
and you want to be able to teach

00:27:34.760 --> 00:27:37.719
with the newer functionality that's been implemented.

00:27:37.719 --> 00:27:41.160
Mid semester, you can update the base project

00:27:41.160 --> 00:27:42.359
so that going forward,

00:27:42.359 --> 00:27:44.760
you're using a newer version of that package

00:27:44.760 --> 00:27:49.280
and every project that's starting from that point onwards

00:27:49.280 --> 00:27:51.040
is affected by this update.

00:27:51.040 --> 00:27:53.599
But it's not retroactive and that's good

00:27:53.599 --> 00:27:55.319
because you're not gonna break old work

00:27:55.319 --> 00:27:56.839
students may have done.

00:27:57.959 --> 00:28:01.599
I think this is also a really nice perk

00:28:01.599 --> 00:28:05.719
because when you are using kind of maybe an RCDO

00:28:05.719 --> 00:28:09.400
in the server type setup that may be shared

00:28:09.400 --> 00:28:12.000
throughout the university or throughout your department

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:13.880
with maybe other instructors,

00:28:13.880 --> 00:28:16.880
oftentimes IT professionals would be hesitant

00:28:16.880 --> 00:28:19.280
to update this sort of base image

00:28:19.280 --> 00:28:22.479
because changes that you make could affect others as well.

00:28:22.479 --> 00:28:26.119
But by the definition of a workspace,

00:28:26.119 --> 00:28:27.719
it's only your class

00:28:27.719 --> 00:28:32.439
and your class is the only set of projects

00:28:32.439 --> 00:28:34.680
who are going to be affected by this change.

00:28:34.680 --> 00:28:36.920
So you really can do as you please.

00:28:38.479 --> 00:28:41.160
So let's talk a little bit about the pros and cons

00:28:41.160 --> 00:28:42.640
of this approach as well.

00:28:42.640 --> 00:28:45.439
We talked about various permission levels as a pro

00:28:45.439 --> 00:28:48.239
and this notion of a base project.

00:28:48.239 --> 00:28:51.079
The notion of assignments which remove the need

00:28:51.079 --> 00:28:54.000
to remind students to make copy of their projects

00:28:54.000 --> 00:28:55.719
before starting their work

00:28:55.719 --> 00:29:00.000
and the ability to peek into student projects

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:03.079
and ability to view stats on student engagement.

00:29:03.079 --> 00:29:05.119
So you can take a look at the dashboard

00:29:05.119 --> 00:29:07.280
to see how much kind of compute

00:29:07.280 --> 00:29:09.160
your students may have been using.

00:29:09.160 --> 00:29:11.760
And I'll mention in a second that we have a package

00:29:11.760 --> 00:29:15.040
that you can use to speak to the RStudio Cloud API

00:29:15.040 --> 00:29:16.719
to get further information

00:29:16.719 --> 00:29:19.560
about which of your students have been active.

00:29:19.560 --> 00:29:22.680
I know a few folks are using that sort of data

00:29:22.680 --> 00:29:25.040
for pedagogical research, for example,

00:29:25.040 --> 00:29:29.680
to quantify engagement of students with the work.

00:29:30.839 --> 00:29:32.040
In the negative side,

00:29:32.040 --> 00:29:34.119
perhaps if I could pick on something

00:29:34.119 --> 00:29:37.560
and I think really here the negatives are very small

00:29:37.560 --> 00:29:39.959
is that when students land in a workspace

00:29:39.959 --> 00:29:41.319
when they get invited,

00:29:41.319 --> 00:29:43.680
they just land in that main page,

00:29:43.680 --> 00:29:45.280
not in an RStudio project.

00:29:45.280 --> 00:29:47.959
So you're gonna wanna spend a minute or two

00:29:47.959 --> 00:29:51.239
orienting your students about what they need to do next.

00:29:51.239 --> 00:29:53.760
But that's the sort of thing you really need to say once

00:29:53.760 --> 00:29:55.920
and then it's quite clear to them what they need to do

00:29:55.920 --> 00:29:57.439
the next time they get there.

00:29:59.359 --> 00:30:03.119
When we talk about things that could be pros or cons,

00:30:03.119 --> 00:30:05.920
the student work counts towards the instructor

00:30:05.920 --> 00:30:08.839
or the institution workspace hours.

00:30:08.839 --> 00:30:10.280
That means that if you,

00:30:10.280 --> 00:30:13.359
if the kind of the free plan is not sufficient

00:30:13.359 --> 00:30:16.439
for the amount of work your students are doing,

00:30:16.439 --> 00:30:17.959
which very well might be the case

00:30:17.959 --> 00:30:20.079
if this is like a semester long course,

00:30:20.079 --> 00:30:24.119
you need to have set up things where the student,

00:30:24.119 --> 00:30:27.599
so their hours will count towards the limits

00:30:27.599 --> 00:30:29.599
that you have set up for your workspace.

00:30:30.880 --> 00:30:33.520
Also another one that could be a pro or a con

00:30:33.520 --> 00:30:37.040
is that instructor controls permission of students projects.

00:30:37.040 --> 00:30:39.760
So if you are running a course

00:30:39.800 --> 00:30:43.400
where you want things to be readily shareable,

00:30:43.400 --> 00:30:45.400
you would perhaps check that box,

00:30:45.400 --> 00:30:47.680
the permission box to allow your students

00:30:47.680 --> 00:30:51.599
to make their projects shareable,

00:30:51.599 --> 00:30:54.079
but by default, it would not be the case.

00:30:55.719 --> 00:30:57.760
So now that we've talked a little bit

00:30:57.760 --> 00:31:01.119
about how to get students into your RStudio cloud space

00:31:01.119 --> 00:31:04.239
and how to share your materials with them,

00:31:04.239 --> 00:31:06.959
I'll kind of try to wrap things up,

00:31:06.959 --> 00:31:09.520
but with some tips before we perhaps move

00:31:09.520 --> 00:31:11.520
into a bit of a Q and A.

00:31:12.359 --> 00:31:15.479
So the first tip that I would mention

00:31:15.479 --> 00:31:19.680
is that changes to an assignment that you make,

00:31:19.680 --> 00:31:21.520
that after a student has started,

00:31:21.520 --> 00:31:23.239
won't propagate to their copy.

00:31:23.239 --> 00:31:26.359
So this is not like Google Docs in a way,

00:31:26.359 --> 00:31:28.400
is I think the best way to describe it.

00:31:28.400 --> 00:31:30.839
When your student makes a copy of a project

00:31:30.839 --> 00:31:32.000
you have set up for them

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:34.319
in either of the sharing approaches,

00:31:34.319 --> 00:31:36.880
they're really taking a snapshot at that time.

00:31:37.760 --> 00:31:39.640
So if you need to change your assignment,

00:31:39.640 --> 00:31:41.199
and I'm sure we've all been there,

00:31:41.199 --> 00:31:42.640
you assign a homework assignment,

00:31:42.640 --> 00:31:44.359
then you realize something is wrong.

00:31:44.359 --> 00:31:45.959
You're gonna need to get that information

00:31:45.959 --> 00:31:47.239
to them in another way,

00:31:47.239 --> 00:31:49.319
or have them start with a new project,

00:31:49.319 --> 00:31:54.040
or have your projects be linked to a Git repository as well.

00:31:54.040 --> 00:31:55.920
And you can change that Git repository

00:31:55.920 --> 00:31:58.160
and ask your students to pull the changes in.

00:31:59.239 --> 00:32:02.880
Packages in the base project are installed, but not loaded.

00:32:02.880 --> 00:32:05.119
So when you're writing your instructions,

00:32:05.119 --> 00:32:07.359
you want to remind yourself,

00:32:07.359 --> 00:32:11.599
remind your students to do library, whatever package name,

00:32:11.599 --> 00:32:13.839
because they won't be able to use it immediately

00:32:13.839 --> 00:32:14.839
in the console.

00:32:17.839 --> 00:32:21.160
This information is always on the RStudio Cloud guide

00:32:21.160 --> 00:32:22.680
and the What's New page.

00:32:22.680 --> 00:32:25.400
RStudio Cloud is still evolving.

00:32:25.400 --> 00:32:30.079
It is not changing in terms of,

00:32:30.079 --> 00:32:31.920
it's not changing in terms of like,

00:32:31.920 --> 00:32:35.319
in a way where it's going to be a completely different UI

00:32:35.319 --> 00:32:37.359
the next day your students land in it,

00:32:37.359 --> 00:32:40.040
but there are new features being added.

00:32:40.040 --> 00:32:43.000
And so it's nice to keep up with those.

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:46.160
And if you encounter any sort of slowness or glitches,

00:32:46.160 --> 00:32:49.040
say your students are reporting, we can't log on,

00:32:49.040 --> 00:32:52.479
there's a current system status link on the side

00:32:52.479 --> 00:32:53.800
that's super handy.

00:32:53.800 --> 00:32:56.560
It allows you to check to see if there are real outage,

00:32:56.560 --> 00:32:58.760
and if not, you can go ahead and report it.

00:32:59.760 --> 00:33:03.000
Other tips is I strongly recommend

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:05.079
creating an additional account.

00:33:05.079 --> 00:33:07.319
So I have this like additional account

00:33:07.319 --> 00:33:10.000
with another personal email address I had,

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:13.560
and I invite that persona as a student,

00:33:13.560 --> 00:33:16.040
so as a contributor into my workspace,

00:33:16.040 --> 00:33:20.319
so that I can log in and see things the students see them.

00:33:20.319 --> 00:33:25.119
That can be helpful when you are kind of taking screenshots

00:33:25.119 --> 00:33:26.400
for your students as well,

00:33:26.400 --> 00:33:28.000
if that's the sort of thing you like to put

00:33:28.400 --> 00:33:29.719
in your instructions.

00:33:31.079 --> 00:33:35.640
You can set computational resources allotted to projects.

00:33:35.640 --> 00:33:38.560
By default, you get a decent amount,

00:33:38.560 --> 00:33:42.680
but if you're working with either bigger data sets,

00:33:42.680 --> 00:33:47.680
or doing something that's more computationally intensive,

00:33:50.160 --> 00:33:53.920
then the default settings would be sufficient for.

00:33:53.920 --> 00:33:57.319
You may wanna up those computational resources

00:33:57.359 --> 00:33:59.959
that are available to each project.

00:33:59.959 --> 00:34:04.160
And the one way to figure out if this is going to be needed

00:34:04.160 --> 00:34:06.079
is to actually test your assignment.

00:34:06.079 --> 00:34:08.159
So if you write answer keys, for example,

00:34:08.159 --> 00:34:10.479
you may try running them in RStudio Cloud

00:34:10.479 --> 00:34:12.120
to make sure things hold up.

00:34:12.120 --> 00:34:15.159
The one place where this can be difficult to foresee

00:34:15.159 --> 00:34:18.320
ahead of time can be if you have open-ended projects

00:34:18.320 --> 00:34:19.239
for your students,

00:34:19.239 --> 00:34:21.919
because then maybe you have no control

00:34:21.919 --> 00:34:23.800
over exactly what they're gonna work on,

00:34:23.800 --> 00:34:25.719
how big a data set they're gonna bring.

00:34:25.719 --> 00:34:28.000
So it's nice to have a feedback loop

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:30.520
and explain to your students a little bit

00:34:31.919 --> 00:34:34.760
that if things are lagging, or slow,

00:34:34.760 --> 00:34:36.600
or just like they're trying to run some code,

00:34:36.600 --> 00:34:38.639
or things are hanging,

00:34:38.639 --> 00:34:41.439
it very well might be that the resources allotted

00:34:41.439 --> 00:34:43.600
aren't sufficient, and they can bring that up to you,

00:34:43.600 --> 00:34:45.040
and you can set that for them

00:34:45.040 --> 00:34:47.199
after they've started the project as well.

00:34:47.199 --> 00:34:49.639
So those are things you can change at any point

00:34:49.639 --> 00:34:50.879
in a project's life.

00:34:51.639 --> 00:34:55.360
I would, the peeking at your students' functionality

00:34:55.360 --> 00:34:59.399
is super nice, but from a pedagogical perspective,

00:34:59.399 --> 00:35:03.840
I would recommend that you use that feature sparingly.

00:35:03.840 --> 00:35:06.719
It's important for us to teach our students

00:35:06.719 --> 00:35:09.520
how to ask good questions without us saying,

00:35:09.520 --> 00:35:12.639
hey, just move away from the keyboard, I'll do it for you.

00:35:12.639 --> 00:35:14.040
Because that's a little bit of that.

00:35:14.040 --> 00:35:16.840
Move away from the computer, let me take over and do it.

00:35:16.840 --> 00:35:20.000
And sometimes that's exactly what a student needs.

00:35:20.000 --> 00:35:22.239
But it's useful for them to try

00:35:22.239 --> 00:35:24.199
to articulate the question first,

00:35:24.199 --> 00:35:25.800
and not go there right away.

00:35:27.360 --> 00:35:30.040
I also use that assignment feature

00:35:30.040 --> 00:35:32.239
for things that are not assignments as well.

00:35:32.239 --> 00:35:35.120
So even if I don't necessarily expect the students

00:35:35.120 --> 00:35:38.199
to complete and turn in something,

00:35:38.199 --> 00:35:39.760
you might still use that feature,

00:35:39.760 --> 00:35:42.360
because it's just a handy feature to say,

00:35:42.360 --> 00:35:44.879
let me get started with where you left things off.

00:35:44.879 --> 00:35:47.040
And so one of the things I do is if I'm doing

00:35:47.040 --> 00:35:49.399
any sort of live coding in class,

00:35:49.800 --> 00:35:52.639
I'll create a skeleton of what I'm gonna get through,

00:35:52.639 --> 00:35:56.360
maybe with some prompts throughout an R Markdown file,

00:35:56.360 --> 00:35:58.719
and leave that as an RStudio Cloud project

00:35:58.719 --> 00:36:02.439
for students to get started with as I start coding as well.

00:36:04.199 --> 00:36:06.879
There are various kind of plans

00:36:06.879 --> 00:36:10.760
that you can choose for RStudio Cloud.

00:36:10.760 --> 00:36:12.520
And there's a free plan as well.

00:36:12.520 --> 00:36:15.439
And for kind of either hobby usage

00:36:15.439 --> 00:36:18.840
or kind of short amounts of teaching,

00:36:19.320 --> 00:36:21.120
what's allowed there,

00:36:21.120 --> 00:36:23.560
allotted there might very well be sufficient.

00:36:23.560 --> 00:36:26.120
But I've found that if I'm teaching a course

00:36:26.120 --> 00:36:29.360
with many students over a 15 week semester,

00:36:29.360 --> 00:36:31.639
I probably need either the instructor

00:36:31.639 --> 00:36:33.639
or the organization plan.

00:36:33.639 --> 00:36:35.600
And if there are questions about the,

00:36:38.639 --> 00:36:42.719
if there are questions about these various plans,

00:36:42.719 --> 00:36:45.159
I will be able to answer them at the end as well.

00:36:46.040 --> 00:36:49.280
I'll also mention the RS Cloud package.

00:36:49.280 --> 00:36:53.439
It's not currently on CRAN, but it is available on GitHub.

00:36:53.439 --> 00:36:55.120
And our goal is to get that on CRAN,

00:36:55.120 --> 00:36:57.600
perhaps sometimes in 2022.

00:36:57.600 --> 00:37:00.560
But it has a nice set of functions where, as you can see,

00:37:00.560 --> 00:37:04.280
you can query the API to get a list of your users,

00:37:04.280 --> 00:37:06.959
to get some information on their statistics,

00:37:06.959 --> 00:37:09.719
like are they still engaging or not?

00:37:09.719 --> 00:37:12.600
You can use it to send invitations.

00:37:12.919 --> 00:37:16.439
So it's almost like you get to upload a roster

00:37:16.439 --> 00:37:18.719
and send invitations to all of your students.

00:37:18.719 --> 00:37:23.199
So if you are using RStudio Cloud heavily,

00:37:23.199 --> 00:37:27.840
and particularly with large groups of members and students,

00:37:27.840 --> 00:37:30.479
the package might very well be helpful for you,

00:37:30.479 --> 00:37:31.520
especially if you're like me

00:37:31.520 --> 00:37:33.399
and you don't like clicking around things too much,

00:37:33.399 --> 00:37:35.639
and you'd rather script things up.

00:37:35.639 --> 00:37:38.439
If you do start working with RS Cloud,

00:37:38.439 --> 00:37:40.719
you're going to need an API key,

00:37:40.719 --> 00:37:43.959
which you can get in the RStudio Cloud UI.

00:37:43.959 --> 00:37:45.439
So just from your profile,

00:37:45.439 --> 00:37:48.199
you can go ahead and request an API key.

00:37:48.199 --> 00:37:50.479
And if there's features that you would like to see

00:37:50.479 --> 00:37:52.479
in this package, please open an issue.

00:37:52.479 --> 00:37:54.199
I'm actively working on it,

00:37:54.199 --> 00:37:56.919
and we'd be happy to try to implement them

00:37:56.919 --> 00:37:59.959
or at least let you know if that's not feasible

00:37:59.959 --> 00:38:01.760
due to the setup of the API.

00:38:03.040 --> 00:38:05.879
And if you would like to learn more about RStudio Cloud,

00:38:05.879 --> 00:38:07.760
Jesse Mostapak has put together

00:38:07.760 --> 00:38:12.000
this really nice playlist of kind of short videos

00:38:12.000 --> 00:38:15.600
on YouTube that are about individual things

00:38:15.600 --> 00:38:18.080
you might want to do on RStudio Cloud.

00:38:19.120 --> 00:38:22.800
So I recommend taking a look at that as well.

00:38:22.800 --> 00:38:25.919
I think there may be stuff you're familiar with,

00:38:25.919 --> 00:38:27.199
but sometimes it's nice to see

00:38:27.199 --> 00:38:28.919
how somebody else approaches it.

00:38:28.919 --> 00:38:30.520
And there very well might be things

00:38:30.520 --> 00:38:32.679
that you didn't know existed there as well.

00:38:33.800 --> 00:38:35.600
All right, I think that's it for me.

00:38:35.600 --> 00:38:38.239
Once again, the slides for this can be found

00:38:38.239 --> 00:38:42.479
at rstd.io slash rsclouddemo.

00:38:42.479 --> 00:38:45.320
And I would be happy to take any questions.

00:38:45.320 --> 00:38:46.399
Thanks for listening.

00:38:49.360 --> 00:38:50.600
Hey, Minae, thank you so much.

00:38:50.600 --> 00:38:53.120
That was super interesting.

00:38:53.120 --> 00:38:57.600
Hopefully our guests walked away learning something new.

00:38:57.600 --> 00:39:01.120
In terms of Q&A, I think we have a few lined up.

00:39:01.120 --> 00:39:03.479
For anyone that might've joined a little late,

00:39:03.479 --> 00:39:05.600
if you do have any questions,

00:39:05.600 --> 00:39:08.439
feel free to enter those on the YouTube live chat

00:39:08.439 --> 00:39:11.439
and we'll be sure to surface them.

00:39:11.439 --> 00:39:12.879
I'm gonna start with a question

00:39:12.879 --> 00:39:14.800
that I actually get pretty often.

00:39:14.800 --> 00:39:16.760
Let me get this up on the screen here.

00:39:16.760 --> 00:39:18.560
So I get asked a lot about base projects.

00:39:18.560 --> 00:39:20.080
Could you talk a little bit more

00:39:20.080 --> 00:39:22.600
about how you handled those scenarios

00:39:22.600 --> 00:39:24.919
before the base project concept existed?

00:39:26.040 --> 00:39:29.000
Yeah, so if I don't have access

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:31.479
to this notion of a base project,

00:39:31.760 --> 00:39:35.919
what that means is that every time I set up an assignment,

00:39:35.919 --> 00:39:37.879
I have to install the packages

00:39:37.879 --> 00:39:39.439
that are needed for that assignment.

00:39:39.439 --> 00:39:42.800
For me, that often means I need to install Tidyverse,

00:39:42.800 --> 00:39:43.639
for example.

00:39:43.639 --> 00:39:45.439
So homework one, install Tidyverse.

00:39:45.439 --> 00:39:46.800
Homework two, install Tidyverse.

00:39:46.800 --> 00:39:49.199
And any other projects as well.

00:39:49.199 --> 00:39:51.919
Another thing is submission instructions

00:39:51.919 --> 00:39:54.879
is also another thing that comes up a lot,

00:39:54.879 --> 00:39:56.959
or any sort of like,

00:39:56.959 --> 00:39:58.320
these are the things you're allowed to do

00:39:58.320 --> 00:39:59.159
for this assignment.

00:39:59.159 --> 00:40:01.080
These are the things you're not allowed to do.

00:40:01.639 --> 00:40:03.919
So I would have this like text file

00:40:05.159 --> 00:40:06.760
that's like a plain text file

00:40:06.760 --> 00:40:08.120
that has this information

00:40:08.120 --> 00:40:11.959
that I would upload to every single assignment.

00:40:11.959 --> 00:40:14.919
The way I tend to teach in a workspace,

00:40:14.919 --> 00:40:19.120
my students are rarely creating a project

00:40:19.120 --> 00:40:20.879
just out of the blue in there.

00:40:20.879 --> 00:40:23.800
They're often starting off of an assignment

00:40:23.800 --> 00:40:25.679
that I have prepared for them.

00:40:25.679 --> 00:40:30.479
So the base projects have mostly made my life easier

00:40:30.479 --> 00:40:33.159
as I create new assignments.

00:40:33.159 --> 00:40:35.360
But every once in a while,

00:40:35.360 --> 00:40:37.399
there may be a situation where your student

00:40:37.399 --> 00:40:39.280
just wants to create a project in there

00:40:39.280 --> 00:40:42.040
and work on something related to the class,

00:40:42.040 --> 00:40:44.959
but maybe not necessarily attached to any assignment.

00:40:44.959 --> 00:40:48.360
And then they get the benefit of using the same R version

00:40:48.360 --> 00:40:49.760
and the version of packages

00:40:49.760 --> 00:40:52.719
that you have pre-installed for them as well.

00:40:52.719 --> 00:40:55.159
The other thing that I really like about the base projects

00:40:55.159 --> 00:40:57.439
is that I can update them throughout the semester

00:40:57.439 --> 00:41:01.000
and they don't break projects that happened in the past.

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:03.040
So student work doesn't get affected,

00:41:03.040 --> 00:41:05.919
but I get to benefit from say a new update

00:41:05.919 --> 00:41:07.679
that may have come up in a package.

00:41:09.479 --> 00:41:10.760
Interesting.

00:41:10.760 --> 00:41:13.320
I see Brad just sent over a question

00:41:13.320 --> 00:41:15.080
that I think you somewhat touched on,

00:41:15.080 --> 00:41:17.479
but just to make sure that they heard the answer.

00:41:17.479 --> 00:41:19.719
Is there a way to distribute data files to students

00:41:19.719 --> 00:41:21.320
without setting up a project?

00:41:22.439 --> 00:41:25.159
So if you're not setting up a project,

00:41:25.159 --> 00:41:26.479
so if you're setting up a project,

00:41:26.479 --> 00:41:28.560
upload it there and then it's distributed.

00:41:28.560 --> 00:41:31.320
If you're not setting up a project,

00:41:31.320 --> 00:41:35.239
there isn't necessarily a RStudio Cloud specific way

00:41:35.239 --> 00:41:37.040
of getting it to them.

00:41:37.040 --> 00:41:41.120
But ways that you might use is if you have access

00:41:41.120 --> 00:41:43.800
to a place where you can upload your data sets

00:41:43.800 --> 00:41:46.239
and that very well might just be a GitHub repository,

00:41:46.239 --> 00:41:48.159
that would be a free place to host them.

00:41:48.159 --> 00:41:51.760
For example, you can host them there

00:41:51.760 --> 00:41:54.159
and then a lot of the data reading functions

00:41:54.159 --> 00:41:56.800
will take a URL as an input as well.

00:41:56.800 --> 00:41:59.000
So even if the data set doesn't exist,

00:41:59.840 --> 00:42:01.040
I don't wanna use the word locally,

00:42:01.040 --> 00:42:02.479
I suppose everything is in the cloud,

00:42:02.479 --> 00:42:05.159
but in that project for those students,

00:42:05.159 --> 00:42:08.959
they can read directly from a URL as well.

00:42:08.959 --> 00:42:12.959
Also, if the goal is to teach students

00:42:12.959 --> 00:42:15.280
how to get data into something,

00:42:15.280 --> 00:42:16.719
what you might do is,

00:42:16.719 --> 00:42:18.239
so this is something I've done as well,

00:42:18.239 --> 00:42:22.199
where sometimes I don't wanna just put the data files

00:42:22.199 --> 00:42:24.159
for them into their files pane,

00:42:24.159 --> 00:42:26.840
I want them to learn how to do that.

00:42:26.840 --> 00:42:28.719
So what I'll do in my instructions

00:42:28.719 --> 00:42:31.840
is I'll have instructions for downloading a data set

00:42:31.840 --> 00:42:34.600
onto their computer so that we can teach them

00:42:34.600 --> 00:42:38.520
how to upload a data set into the RStudio Cloud project.

00:42:38.520 --> 00:42:39.919
And the reason why I do that

00:42:39.919 --> 00:42:41.840
with some of my earlier assignments

00:42:41.840 --> 00:42:43.959
is that for their final project,

00:42:43.959 --> 00:42:46.120
they have to find a data set and bring it in.

00:42:46.120 --> 00:42:49.320
So I wanna make sure that they have had some practice

00:42:49.320 --> 00:42:51.159
with bringing in their own data set

00:42:51.159 --> 00:42:52.959
before we get to that point.

00:42:53.919 --> 00:42:55.840
That makes a ton of sense.

00:42:55.840 --> 00:42:58.040
Looks like the next question,

00:42:58.040 --> 00:43:01.080
lots of instructors use a learning management system.

00:43:01.080 --> 00:43:03.120
So curious, how have you handled grading?

00:43:05.199 --> 00:43:08.280
So the way I have been teaching

00:43:08.280 --> 00:43:10.919
over the last five or six years

00:43:10.919 --> 00:43:14.320
is that I actually teach version control

00:43:14.320 --> 00:43:16.360
alongside data science.

00:43:16.360 --> 00:43:18.479
And every single assignment

00:43:18.479 --> 00:43:21.120
is not only an RStudio Cloud project,

00:43:21.120 --> 00:43:23.639
but it's also a GitHub repository.

00:43:23.639 --> 00:43:27.360
And so we actually do our submission in a way

00:43:27.360 --> 00:43:29.919
or grading by pushing to GitHub ultimately.

00:43:30.800 --> 00:43:35.120
There is currently not a grading feature in RStudio Cloud.

00:43:35.120 --> 00:43:37.879
So there's not a way where like maybe assigned

00:43:37.879 --> 00:43:39.360
to each project, you know,

00:43:39.360 --> 00:43:43.360
not a place where you can actually store a grade with it.

00:43:43.360 --> 00:43:45.919
But I believe that's like in the pipeline

00:43:46.479 --> 00:43:47.320
of at least feature requests

00:43:47.320 --> 00:43:51.760
that has come from other instructors as well.

00:43:51.760 --> 00:43:55.800
So that very well might be something that's included later.

00:43:55.800 --> 00:43:58.520
Even in instances where we've had grading,

00:43:58.520 --> 00:44:01.000
but no like version control

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:03.719
or GitHub associated with my teaching,

00:44:03.719 --> 00:44:06.479
I would have either myself or my TAs

00:44:06.479 --> 00:44:09.360
go into the particular projects.

00:44:09.360 --> 00:44:12.040
And the nice thing is if you have an assignment

00:44:12.040 --> 00:44:13.399
that you have set up,

00:44:13.439 --> 00:44:16.000
the title of that assignment is always the same.

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:18.360
I guess your students could mess you up and change them,

00:44:18.360 --> 00:44:19.959
but they generally don't.

00:44:19.959 --> 00:44:23.080
So what you end up seeing is let's say your homework one,

00:44:23.080 --> 00:44:26.360
and then you can see, as I saw on my slides,

00:44:26.360 --> 00:44:28.520
like view derived projects,

00:44:28.520 --> 00:44:33.360
and you can go through, go into your students' projects,

00:44:33.360 --> 00:44:34.639
grade their work.

00:44:34.639 --> 00:44:37.520
And oftentimes what I'll have is like a CSV file

00:44:37.520 --> 00:44:40.320
I keep locally where I enter the final grades.

00:44:40.320 --> 00:44:44.639
You can create new files in their projects as well

00:44:44.639 --> 00:44:47.439
to leave them feedback if you would like to as well.

00:44:49.959 --> 00:44:50.800
Thank you.

00:44:50.800 --> 00:44:53.280
I see Ryan just sent across a question.

00:44:54.159 --> 00:44:57.479
Would you recommend a particular PKI key management package

00:44:57.479 --> 00:44:59.959
that works well with RStudio Cloud?

00:44:59.959 --> 00:45:02.719
Say like I'm pulling data from Qualtrics.

00:45:04.199 --> 00:45:06.600
I have to ask what PKI is

00:45:06.600 --> 00:45:09.239
because I'm not sure what it stands for.

00:45:09.280 --> 00:45:11.360
Maybe I could find out for myself.

00:45:13.199 --> 00:45:15.239
Or maybe it'll come into the chat.

00:45:17.120 --> 00:45:20.879
Ryan, if you can clarify what PKI is,

00:45:20.879 --> 00:45:25.879
I would be happy to try to answer that question.

00:45:26.159 --> 00:45:29.439
Public key infrastructure, I think maybe is what it is.

00:45:31.639 --> 00:45:32.479
Good question.

00:45:32.479 --> 00:45:34.679
So this would be something where you basically

00:45:34.679 --> 00:45:39.679
want to store some sort of public key in your project.

00:45:41.959 --> 00:45:46.959
I'm gonna say the closest experience I have to this

00:45:47.399 --> 00:45:52.399
is maybe storing my personal access token for GitHub,

00:45:55.040 --> 00:45:56.199
which you can do.

00:45:56.199 --> 00:46:00.840
So however you're storing these in an R session,

00:46:00.840 --> 00:46:02.760
if you're working locally,

00:46:02.760 --> 00:46:06.000
you should be able to do so on RStudio Cloud as well.

00:46:06.000 --> 00:46:10.280
One thing I'll mention is any sort of user level information

00:46:10.280 --> 00:46:13.959
as such does not get shared between your projects

00:46:13.959 --> 00:46:15.879
in your RStudio Cloud profile.

00:46:15.879 --> 00:46:18.760
So you would have to set those things

00:46:18.760 --> 00:46:22.320
on a per project basis, which can be a hassle,

00:46:22.320 --> 00:46:24.679
or it might be actually a positive

00:46:24.679 --> 00:46:28.280
if you're actually trying to test access levels

00:46:28.280 --> 00:46:29.639
with various keys.

00:46:30.479 --> 00:46:33.399
But, and I don't have a recommendation

00:46:33.399 --> 00:46:34.479
for a specific package,

00:46:34.479 --> 00:46:36.479
but whatever has worked for you locally

00:46:36.479 --> 00:46:39.520
should work on RStudio Cloud as well for that.

00:46:40.879 --> 00:46:41.719
Thanks, Mina.

00:46:41.719 --> 00:46:45.639
I see Ryan did confirm that that meant public keys.

