00:53:14.199 --> 00:53:18.080
And I think that if it seems like a useful thing to do,

00:53:18.080 --> 00:53:19.959
like my goal is to try to get that package

00:53:19.959 --> 00:53:21.600
on CRAN sometime this year.

00:53:21.600 --> 00:53:22.919
It's currently functional,

00:53:22.919 --> 00:53:25.800
but there are a few feature requests in there

00:53:25.800 --> 00:53:27.199
that we haven't done.

00:53:27.199 --> 00:53:29.639
Maybe when we do that, we can try to do one of these

00:53:29.639 --> 00:53:33.560
where we do a more extensive kind of demo of it as well.

00:53:35.280 --> 00:53:36.120
Perfect.

00:53:37.560 --> 00:53:38.879
Brad, I did see your question

00:53:38.879 --> 00:53:41.280
regarding how are students counted.

00:53:41.280 --> 00:53:46.280
It really depends on your membership type.

00:53:46.479 --> 00:53:48.320
So happy to take that offline.

00:53:48.320 --> 00:53:49.520
I just threw my email in there

00:53:49.520 --> 00:53:50.560
if you wanna follow up with me,

00:53:50.560 --> 00:53:53.739
and we can clarify that for your particular use case.

00:53:55.639 --> 00:53:58.040
Let's see, we have about five more minutes.

00:54:00.040 --> 00:54:01.439
Here is a good one.

00:54:01.439 --> 00:54:04.280
Do instructors have to cover all students' costs?

00:54:05.399 --> 00:54:06.840
I think the answer is no.

00:54:06.879 --> 00:54:11.399
It really depends on how you want to approach this.

00:54:11.399 --> 00:54:14.080
So I will tell you about my experience

00:54:14.080 --> 00:54:15.959
of the various things that we've done,

00:54:15.959 --> 00:54:17.600
like kind of on the instructor side,

00:54:17.600 --> 00:54:21.360
and then Pete might have more to add on that as well.

00:54:21.360 --> 00:54:24.600
I think that one of the things you may wanna consider is,

00:54:24.600 --> 00:54:27.000
am I the only instructor at my institution

00:54:27.000 --> 00:54:28.320
who is doing this?

00:54:28.320 --> 00:54:30.399
Or are there other instructors as well,

00:54:30.399 --> 00:54:32.959
say various courses in a given department?

00:54:32.959 --> 00:54:36.120
Because this notion of instead of an instructor account,

00:54:36.120 --> 00:54:38.800
an organization account might actually be

00:54:38.800 --> 00:54:40.000
the right fit for you,

00:54:40.000 --> 00:54:41.479
especially if you have students

00:54:41.479 --> 00:54:43.760
who are taking like multiple classes

00:54:43.760 --> 00:54:46.639
for which they might be using RStudio Cloud for.

00:54:46.639 --> 00:54:49.120
That was the setup that we had last year

00:54:49.120 --> 00:54:51.959
when I was at the University of Edinburgh.

00:54:51.959 --> 00:54:54.159
And I believe coming down the pipeline,

00:54:54.159 --> 00:54:55.439
if it's not live now,

00:54:55.439 --> 00:54:59.800
is a notion where students could pay for access

00:54:59.800 --> 00:55:02.919
even though they're in your workspace, right Pete?

00:55:02.919 --> 00:55:03.760
That's correct.

00:55:04.000 --> 00:55:07.760
Historically, the instructor,

00:55:07.760 --> 00:55:09.199
again, depending on membership type,

00:55:09.199 --> 00:55:10.479
is either gonna cover the cost,

00:55:10.479 --> 00:55:11.800
the school's gonna cover the cost,

00:55:11.800 --> 00:55:14.320
or if the students do directly cover the cost.

00:55:14.320 --> 00:55:16.159
Today, there might not actually be an integration

00:55:16.159 --> 00:55:18.439
between the student's account and the instructor's account,

00:55:18.439 --> 00:55:19.560
which as you can imagine,

00:55:19.560 --> 00:55:22.639
can be a little limiting when it comes to nice features

00:55:22.639 --> 00:55:23.639
like being able to peek in

00:55:23.639 --> 00:55:25.879
and see how your students are doing.

00:55:25.879 --> 00:55:28.239
So as Mine just alluded to,

00:55:28.239 --> 00:55:32.360
we are working on a new plan where if you'd like,

00:55:32.399 --> 00:55:36.879
students could actually pay for their actual usage.

00:55:36.879 --> 00:55:38.679
So there's gonna be more options

00:55:38.679 --> 00:55:40.679
for how to spin up RStudio Cloud

00:55:40.679 --> 00:55:43.360
for your particular use case at your institution.

00:55:43.360 --> 00:55:46.040
We're hoping to provide that new option

00:55:46.040 --> 00:55:48.919
in the next week or two if things stay on track.

00:55:52.679 --> 00:55:54.600
Let's see, so a couple more minutes here.

00:55:54.600 --> 00:55:56.760
Do have a few more questions trickling in.

00:55:58.080 --> 00:56:00.000
To try RStudio Cloud,

00:56:00.000 --> 00:56:04.080
is the free tier robust or should I trial a paid tier?

00:56:04.080 --> 00:56:06.479
I think that the free tier is,

00:56:06.479 --> 00:56:10.560
there is no, I mean, in terms of things

00:56:10.560 --> 00:56:12.600
that I would consider robustness,

00:56:12.600 --> 00:56:15.719
there should be no reason why you can't try things out

00:56:15.719 --> 00:56:16.600
with the free tier.

00:56:16.600 --> 00:56:19.479
I think you end up running into limitations

00:56:19.479 --> 00:56:21.959
of the free tier really when you are trying

00:56:21.959 --> 00:56:24.320
to offer a particular type of experience

00:56:24.320 --> 00:56:26.479
to either a large group of people

00:56:26.479 --> 00:56:28.479
or over an extended period of time.

00:56:28.479 --> 00:56:31.439
So I know from an instructional perspective,

00:56:31.439 --> 00:56:35.360
lots of folks who run short courses or workshops

00:56:35.360 --> 00:56:37.760
who just use the free tier for that.

00:56:39.080 --> 00:56:41.080
Yeah, in my experience, the free tier

00:56:41.080 --> 00:56:42.919
is not really too limiting

00:56:42.919 --> 00:56:44.679
in terms of features or capabilities.

00:56:44.679 --> 00:56:47.719
It's more so the amount of time you have access to it

00:56:47.719 --> 00:56:51.120
in a given month and the amount of collaborators,

00:56:51.120 --> 00:56:53.600
users that you can share projects with.

00:56:54.600 --> 00:56:55.439
Let's see.

00:56:55.439 --> 00:56:57.840
So depending on course type,

00:56:57.840 --> 00:56:59.320
does it make sense to use cloud

00:56:59.320 --> 00:57:01.000
for the entirety of the course

00:57:01.000 --> 00:57:02.399
or to have students transition

00:57:02.399 --> 00:57:04.000
to local machines at some point?

00:57:04.840 --> 00:57:06.120
So that's a really good question

00:57:06.120 --> 00:57:07.679
and a question that often comes up.

00:57:07.679 --> 00:57:09.520
I'm often like whenever I make a pitch

00:57:09.520 --> 00:57:10.879
for let's teach on the cloud,

00:57:10.879 --> 00:57:11.719
the first thing is,

00:57:11.719 --> 00:57:15.399
but don't we need to learn to install and potentially yes.

00:57:15.399 --> 00:57:17.639
So first of all, I'll couch this with,

00:57:17.639 --> 00:57:18.800
well, it really depends

00:57:18.800 --> 00:57:21.159
on the learning goals of your course, right?

00:57:21.159 --> 00:57:23.360
If part of the learning goals of your course

00:57:23.600 --> 00:57:24.959
is software installation,

00:57:24.959 --> 00:57:28.040
then yes, it does make sense to transition.

00:57:28.040 --> 00:57:30.080
I'll give you my perspective of someone

00:57:30.080 --> 00:57:35.080
who generally uses, teaches introductory courses.

00:57:36.320 --> 00:57:38.199
I like starting things on the cloud.

00:57:38.199 --> 00:57:40.760
And one of the things that I try to make sure

00:57:40.760 --> 00:57:42.600
that the students understand

00:57:42.600 --> 00:57:45.719
is that the cloud is not just this esoteric thing.

00:57:45.719 --> 00:57:47.679
It actually is somebody else's machine.

00:57:47.679 --> 00:57:49.360
So we wanna make sure that

00:57:49.360 --> 00:57:51.280
before students leave your course,

00:57:52.040 --> 00:57:53.679
they understand what it means

00:57:53.679 --> 00:57:55.439
for things to live on the cloud,

00:57:55.439 --> 00:57:57.120
which means if they then get involved

00:57:57.120 --> 00:57:58.959
with say a research project

00:57:58.959 --> 00:58:01.760
that might have private data associated with it,

00:58:01.760 --> 00:58:04.239
they shouldn't just upload it to RStudio Cloud

00:58:04.239 --> 00:58:06.159
without making sure that that's okay.

00:58:06.159 --> 00:58:07.760
So I think it's important

00:58:07.760 --> 00:58:10.439
to explain to students what that is.

00:58:10.439 --> 00:58:13.520
If you would like to teach installation as part of it,

00:58:13.520 --> 00:58:15.439
because you think that would be a useful thing

00:58:15.439 --> 00:58:17.639
for students to learn,

00:58:17.639 --> 00:58:21.080
maybe to continue to engage with RStudio down the line,

00:58:21.879 --> 00:58:23.360
even if they're not taking a course

00:58:23.360 --> 00:58:25.919
that uses any of this cloud access,

00:58:25.919 --> 00:58:28.520
then absolutely, I think it's super helpful

00:58:28.520 --> 00:58:29.919
to point them to resources

00:58:29.919 --> 00:58:32.360
or take a bit of class time to do it.

00:58:32.360 --> 00:58:34.679
And the nice thing about doing it later

00:58:34.679 --> 00:58:38.560
is that they're not both new to R and installation issues.

00:58:38.560 --> 00:58:40.959
So they are going to be able to distinguish

00:58:40.959 --> 00:58:42.919
between what is an R error

00:58:42.919 --> 00:58:44.280
versus what might be an error

00:58:44.280 --> 00:58:47.239
that might be happening due to my setup.

00:58:47.239 --> 00:58:50.959
So I think that doing that later on in the course

00:58:51.639 --> 00:58:52.719
can have some of those benefits.

00:58:52.719 --> 00:58:55.000
And the last thing I'll say on this is,

00:58:55.000 --> 00:58:59.360
when people then go on to do things past university life,

00:58:59.360 --> 00:59:01.639
chances are they're gonna continue to do it on the cloud.

00:59:01.639 --> 00:59:03.959
I mean, I think very few industry jobs

00:59:03.959 --> 00:59:06.120
allow you to just like bring your own laptop

00:59:06.120 --> 00:59:07.560
and compute on it.

00:59:07.560 --> 00:59:10.280
And also a lot of academic computing

00:59:10.280 --> 00:59:12.679
happens on research computing clusters as well.

00:59:12.679 --> 00:59:15.520
So this notion of doing things on the cloud

00:59:15.520 --> 00:59:17.719
happens to ease onboarding,

00:59:17.719 --> 00:59:20.040
but it's not just some baby steps thing

00:59:20.040 --> 00:59:22.600
that's not a realistic situation, I think.

00:59:23.919 --> 00:59:24.760
Interesting.

00:59:24.760 --> 00:59:26.919
So we're coming down to the last minute here.

00:59:26.919 --> 00:59:28.479
So just one final question

00:59:28.479 --> 00:59:30.320
that I think should be pretty straightforward.

00:59:30.320 --> 00:59:34.080
Does Workbench have the same virtual classroom capability

00:59:34.080 --> 00:59:36.080
which cloud provides?

00:59:36.080 --> 00:59:37.959
I'm gonna say yes and no.

00:59:37.959 --> 00:59:41.919
Absolutely yes, in the sense that you can have

00:59:41.919 --> 00:59:44.520
like packages pre-installed for your students

00:59:44.520 --> 00:59:48.600
and you can put some files in there, right?

00:59:48.600 --> 00:59:50.280
And then they can just have them as well.

00:59:50.280 --> 00:59:52.719
You can like associate it with a file system

00:59:52.719 --> 00:59:54.879
and they can authenticate and work there.

00:59:54.879 --> 00:59:57.560
The no part is really on the UI, I think.

00:59:57.560 --> 01:00:00.159
So you don't have this notion of projects

01:00:00.159 --> 01:00:02.239
the same way RStudio Cloud projects

01:00:02.239 --> 01:00:05.520
we could see on the user interface of the learning page.

01:00:05.520 --> 01:00:09.639
There's not a notion of an assignment either.

01:00:09.639 --> 01:00:12.760
So there are some of these kind of the nice bells and whistles

01:00:12.760 --> 01:00:14.120
or various roles.

01:00:14.120 --> 01:00:16.479
These are not things that you are going to have

01:00:16.479 --> 01:00:18.399
by default with Workbench,

01:00:19.199 --> 01:00:21.159
but does it allow compute on the cloud

01:00:21.159 --> 01:00:23.199
with the RStudio IDE interface?

01:00:23.199 --> 01:00:24.080
Absolutely.

01:00:25.199 --> 01:00:26.040
Awesome.

01:00:26.040 --> 01:00:27.959
Well, Mine, it looks like we're at time.

01:00:27.959 --> 01:00:29.560
Really appreciate this.

01:00:29.560 --> 01:00:32.159
And again, I hope all folks that joined

01:00:32.159 --> 01:00:34.919
and were able to tune in and ask questions

01:00:34.919 --> 01:00:36.800
walked away learning something new.

01:00:36.800 --> 01:00:39.439
If anyone was only able to come on

01:00:39.439 --> 01:00:40.520
for the last couple of minutes,

01:00:40.520 --> 01:00:44.120
we did record this so it'll be fully available shortly.

01:00:44.120 --> 01:00:47.360
And again, this is our last event in this live cloud series.

01:00:47.360 --> 01:00:50.239
We are hoping to do another live cloud series

01:00:50.239 --> 01:00:51.639
in a few months.

01:00:51.639 --> 01:00:54.280
And with that, I will wish everyone a good day.

